======================================================================
STRUCTURAL ARGUMENT ATTEMPT
======================================================================

For alpha_1=3:
  c3=3 at n>=7: three 3-cycles that pairwise share a vertex.
  Helly property: 3 pairwise intersecting sets of size 3 in universe of
  size >= 7 need NOT have a common element.
  Without common vertex: can arrange the 3 cycles to use 7 vertices,
  but then the tournament on those 7 vertices must have c3=3 exactly.
  Score seq constraint: c3 = C(7,3) - sum C(s_i,2) = 35 - sum C(s_i,2)
  For c3=3: sum C(s_i,2) = 32. Near-transitive (lots of score spread).
  But 3 non-common-vertex 3-cycles at n=7 almost always generate
  5-cycles and additional 3-cycles, pushing alpha_1 above 3.
  So alpha_1=3 requires very specific structure => forces alpha_2>=2.

For alpha_1=10:
  At n=6: RIGID. Only score (1,2,2,3,3,4), c3=6+4dc5=10.
  At n>=7: Need 10 directed odd cycles total (3+5+7-cycles).
  With alpha_2=0: ALL 10 cycles pairwise share a vertex.
  10 pairwise overlapping odd cycles on 7+ vertices:
  Each cycle uses >= 3 vertices. If all are 3-cycles, c3=10,
  and c3 = C(n,3) - sum C(s_i,2).
  At n=7: c3=10 means sum C(s_i,2)=25 out of C(7,3)=35.
  score (0,2,2,3,3,4,7-1=6)? -> sum = 0+1+1+3+3+6+?

  Score sequences with c3=10 at n=7 (sum C(s_i,2) = 25):
    (1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 4): c3=10, sum C(s_i,2)=25
    (1, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 5): c3=10, sum C(s_i,2)=25
    (2, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4, 5): c3=10, sum C(s_i,2)=25
